arkation.</span> Mainlines, connectors, and clearance lines must all combine to support movement of heavy and/or oversized equipment. <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">To ensure that military needs are factored into railroad industry decisions that may impact on national defense, the Department of Defense relies on the Military Traffic Management Command (MTMC).</span> In this capacity, <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">MTMC [which] identifies facilities of the railroad infrastructure important to national defense, informs the commercial and civil sectors of Defense needs, and encourages the retention and upkeep of railroad assets vital to support military movements. To ensure this continuity and coordination, MTMC has created the [STRACNET]</span> Strategic <span style="color: #000000; text-decoration: none;">[[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/facility/stracnet.htm|Rail Corridor]]</span> Network (STRACNET). <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">STRACNET has identified 32,500 miles of rail line critical for movement of essential military equipment</span> to ports located <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">around the country as well as another 5,000 miles of track essential to connect one facility to another.</span>In addition to identifying key lines and facilities, MTMC also conducts analysis of potential railroad industry construction, mergers, <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">bankruptcies, and abandonments</span> to determine how any of these actions <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">may affect [and] DOD mobility capabilities</span>. Since 1976, MTMC has reviewed more than 2,100 abandonments affecting 33,000 miles of track, as well as eight bankruptcies affecting more 1/3 of the nation's <span style="color: #000000; text-decoration: none;">[[http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/facility/stracnet.htm|railroad network]]</span>. <span style="font-size: 14.6667px;">MTMC analysis and reviews are the main source of DOD input to the railroad industry in 